NOTES: ﻿https://www.hist-stmarys.org/history ; very likely this church. While the cathedral is more prominent, this historic church predates all the rest in the city, and it stands to reason that, based on that fact, the St. Mary's that we see in later years refers to this church.

﻿https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Louis_Roman_Catholic_Church#:~:text=Saint%20Louis%20Roman%20Catholic%20Church,Roman%20Catholic%20Diocese%20of%20Buffalo%22. ; while St. Joseph's is more notable, and is the main church in the later almanac years of the 1860s/1870s, it appears that this is the only surviving pre-1833 church in the city. For that reason, I am going with this church as opposed to the one that appears first in the diocese later on.

﻿https://stmaryofthesnow.org/history-of-st-mary-of-the-snow ; odd case of a place close to one diocese going with another - this place is right by albany, but, according to this church history, was attached with ny around the time of the civil war

﻿This church is in what is today Syracuse; however, at the time, Salina appears to have had a further reach, meaning this church would've likely been part of Salina: https://www.stjohnthebaptist-holytrinity.com/about/
﻿Hard to identify which one - there are too many in Troy in later years

﻿St. Mary's Select School for Young Ladies

courses: ﻿The course of instruction in this Institution embraces Orthography, Reading, Writing, Grammar, Composition, Ancient and Modern History, Geography, with the use of the Globes, Practical and Rational Arithmetic, Botany, Natural Philosophy, Chemistry; also, Plain and Ornamental Needle-work, Tapestry, Lace-work, Cotton Embroidery, &c.

instNote: ﻿The object of this institution is to clothe, board and educate poor children who have but one parent living.
